## Extended question - Azobenzene {#sec:Azobenzene}

<span style="color: darkcyan;"> *Azobenzene undergoes the following cis-trans isomerisation, the isomerisation occurs in the ps timescale.* \span

```{r echo=FALSE, cistransazobenzene, out.width='70%', fig.show='hold', fig.align='center', fig.cap='The cis-trans isomerisation of azobenzene'}
knitr::include_graphics("images/cistransazobenzene.png")
```

<span style="color: darkcyan;"> - *Why would you expect the absorption spectrum of each isomer to be different?* \span

<span style="color: darkcyan;"> - *Suggest why the trans conformation is more stable than the cis isomer.* \span

 <span style="color: darkcyan;">- *Use the following data to predict the proportion of each isomer under 360 nm excitation.* \span

 <span style="color: darkcyan;"> *Table: (\#tab:azobenzeneabs) The molar extinction coefficient of the two isomers of azobenzene.* \span

| | ε~360~ / M^−1^ cm^−1^ | ε~460~ / M^−1^ cm^−1^|
|:--------------|:---------|:---------|
| trans-azobenzene | 22000 | 4500 |
| cis-azobenzene |2100 | 5500 |
 
<span style="color: darkcyan;"> - *Would there be more or less trans azobenzene at 460 nm? Justify your answer.* \span


<span style="color: darkcyan;"> - *It has been suggested the 360 nm absorption is an S~0~ → S~2~ absorption, and the 460 nm band is an S~0~ → S~1~ absorption. Suggest which energy levels are involved for each of the two transitions and compare it to stilbene which has a similar structure, but the cis and trans absorptions are 280 & 295 nm respectively.* \span

```{r echo=FALSE, stilbene, out.width='30%', fig.show='hold', fig.align='center', fig.cap='The  structure of stilbene'}
knitr::include_graphics("images/stilbene.png")
```

